message: i lit up 6 light bulbs. there were no challenges really. I could definitely send longer messages using binary.
it was more difficult, but that's only because I used binary and I'm not the best at math. the main challenge was adding all the numbers together, but it wasn't that difficult to me.

I used binary to encode the letters and numbers. Bob could figure it out if we talked about it before and if he has knowledge of the binary system. if he has no clue how the binary system works he will most likely not know what I tried to tell him.
I managed to make it work easily, as before I used the binary system. four light bulbs was about enough. with four light bulbs you can represent the number up to 15.
instead of assigning the lightbulbs numbers I assign them letters. then using the binary system I can represent the letters.
we need way more lightbulbs, and energy, its time consuming, etc.
three lightbulbs, if you add 1 + 2 + 4 you get 7. and now using the binary system you can represent the numbers up to seven.

well with half on you could represent half numbers. or when it comes to letters with half and fully lit lightbulbs you could represent how many times the letter is needed. for example if fully lit means the letter is double (bob) that could change a lot.
it was really fun to do this exercise. since I already had experience with binary it was a bit too easy for me but that's just me.
